Chapter 1
Corlen
It was 4:30 am in the Italian time. Corlen disliked waking up so early. The main reason was that he had to wake up the rest of the team. He quietly got out of bed, put on his combat uniform, and strapped on his tactical vest. He carefully gathered his belongings from the storage cabinet and picked up a small special box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder, hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt, and made sure it was equipped with a full set of gear, including a respirator, goggles, and other necessary items. After checking the ammunition pouch, he quietly walked out of the barracks, his boots making crunching sounds on the mud and ice.
He took out a lighter from one pocket and a cigarette from another. After lighting the cigarette, he took a gentle puff and then opened the door. In the past week, he had to strain his brain to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used the pre-set alarm clock because half the time it didn't ring, and all he could hear from the megaphone was a faint hiss.
"Time to wake them up?" Corlen turned around to see Lieutenant Nemicchi approaching.
“Yes.” Corlen replied.
“What are you going to use this time?”
Corlen hadn't even had a chance to answer when the door opened and Harris, Kreis, and a few others rushed out, all dressed and ready to go.
“Good morning,” Kreis said.
“What woke you guys up?” Corlen asked.
"First of all, we don't want to see what method you'll use to wake us up today. Secondly, the first team to wake up can enjoy breakfast first," a soldier named Ravi said. "You know how bad those breakfasts are."
Corlen said, "You're right, Ravi soldier." He pressed the button. The loud alarm sounded in the barracks, and he heard voices shouting loudly and footsteps rushing inside.
"Great, Valturri," Nemic said. "I thought they should have learned to wake up with you by now."
"My brothers from the new recruit training camp did," Corlen said, pointing to Harris, Kreis, and Ravi. "But, to be fair, their platoon leader and squad leader know to wake up before the soldiers."
A few seconds later, the rest of the platoon rushed out, all dressed and ready to go. Some of the new recruits looked sleepy, while others seemed very annoyed.
“Good morning,” Corlen said cheerfully.
“To be frank, sir, why did you wake us up that way?” a private asked.
“Because those ordinary alarm clocks are just junk. And Daybreak never sleeps in,” Corlen replied.
“Take your personal belongings,” Corlen continued. As a lieutenant and deputy commander of the platoon, he had a responsibility to assist Platoon Leader Borealis Sho to supervise and lead the platoon. “We won't be back. All soldiers and lieutenants, you have 15 minutes to do a final check and bring the necessary rations for today.”
The members of Exodus Platoon quickly dispersed. They were part of the 2nd Infantry Division's 2nd Ranger Regiment before the merge. Originally, they were two independent platoons, Cohort and Dagger. This was a elite platoon, and Corlen's feelings about being promoted to lieutenant were complex, with many reasons.
Corlen and Lieutenant Nemic walked side by side on the brightly lit road of the base, with red lights on both sides powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, which helped them avoid enemy bombers. Daybreak had begun to employ the "Wild Boar" tactic in the air and on the ground to attack them.
“New day, new mission for the Hellraisers,” Nemic joked. “Where are they sending us this time?”
“A forward base on the outskirts of Ianloos City. We're being sent to support the ground attack,” Corlen said, taking a puff of his cigarette. He was a bit annoyed that Kreis had gotten him hooked on smoking, but thinking back to the past year, they had been through countless battles, so he said nothing.
“This is terrible. The front-line situation is dire,” Nemic whispered. “All the news coming out of here is 'Support the War, Aid the Kurgan Frontline,' why not support the Hawran Frontline instead?”
“Well said, brother,” Corlen said, flicking the cigarette butt into the mud. “We're marching with the First Armor Platoon, so we don't have to walk. Lieutenant Colonel Shaw should be there.”
“Lieutenant Commander Sho is asking us to drive?” Nemich asked with some surprise.
“Yes. To be honest, he's not as bad as I thought. I mean, he's not great, but he's not unlikable either.”
Corlen raised his thumb and index finger, pressing the microphone on his throat, and shifted his backpack to his back. “Exodus platoon, all units, assemble at the Western Vehicle Depot after completing the task. We will depart with the 1st Armor Platoon at 05:00.”
Every few seconds, he would receive a response from the sergeants. When they first joined, Harris, Kreis, and Ravi were lower-ranking soldiers. Since their basic training on Earth, the four of them had been close friends. Corlen felt like he had known them for a long time, although it had only been less than two years. They were all sergeants, but since last week, when the previous platoon leader was hit by a Daybreak sniper and retired due to injury, Kreis had taken over leading the 2nd Platoon.
When they arrived at the vehicle depot, Corlen and Nemich's gaze fell on about eight Chronos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored cars. The crew members were rushing around, ensuring that their war machines were in working order. Corlen quickly found Lieutenant Commander Sho in the crowd, talking to the commander of the armor platoon. As they approached, Sho looked at them and greeted them, his normally expressionless face showing no emotion.
“Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturri...” he said, Corlen slowing down, Shaw looking at Corlen's gun holster, then up. “The platoon should be ready by now?”
